MobileViT (2021) - The Simpler Hybrid
MobileViT is a hybrid model that uses CNNs to capture local details (textures, edges) and Transformers to capture global context (overall shape and relationships) .

How It Works (Simple Version)
Image → CNN (learns local features) → Transformer (learns global relationships) → CNN → Result

The Key Insight
Instead of applying Transformer to the whole image (which is expensive), MobileViT:
Unfolds the image into small patches
Applies Transformer only to those patches to understand patch-to-patch relationships
Folds them back into a full image 

Why It's Good for Your Waste Project
Benefit			Explanation
Smaller			5.3-5.6 million parameters (vs ResNet50's 25.6M) 
Fast			~18ms per image on mobile hardware 
Accurate		85%+ accuracy on image classification 
Easy to explain	"CNN for details, Transformer for the big picture"


Simple Architecture Diagram:

Input Image
    ↓
[Convolution Blocks] → Learns textures, edges, local patterns
    ↓
[MobileViT Block] → Learns how patches relate to each other
    ↓
[Convolution Blocks] → Fuses local + global features
    ↓
Classification Output

Why Transfer Learning
Use of ImageNet-pretrained MobileViT weights. Even though ImageNet doesn't have waste classes, it provides strong foundational features for texture and shape recognition

Why Two-Phase Training
Phase	    What	                            Why
Phase 1	    Freeze backbone, train classifier	Preserve pretrained features while adapting to waste classes
Phase 2	    Unfreeze, fine-tune entire model	Gradually adjust features for waste domain

This prevents catastrophic forgetting - the model doesn't 'forget' its pretrained knowledge while learning waste-specific features

Training Strategy

Hyperparameter Selection
Hyperparameter	        Value	    Justification
Batch size	            32          Balances memory and gradient stability
Learning rate (Phase 1)	1e-3	    Higher for training new classifier
Learning rate (Phase 2)	1e-5	    Lower for fine-tuning backbone
Optimizer	            AdamW	    Better weight decay control than Adam
Epochs (Phase 1)	    20	        Sufficient for classifier adaptation
Epochs (Phase 2)	    30-50	    Gradual backbone fine-tuning

Addressing Class Imbalance
The 52:1 imbalance is a critical challenge. We address it through:
Method	                            How It Helps
Weighted loss function	            Rare classes get higher loss weight
Oversampling minority classes	    Duplicate rare class images during training
Data augmentation	                More augmentation for minority classes

Loss Function
to use weighted cross-entropy loss where each class gets weight = 1 / (frequency). This forces the model to pay more attention to rare classes like bottle-oil-full.
